The earliest works of Vergil were possibly some or all of the minor pieces known as the Culex (Gnat), Ciris, Moretum (Salacl), Copa (Hostess); but the authenticity of all these is open to question. His fame as a poet began with the publication, prior to Β.0. 35, of the Ecloyae or Bucolica, ten brief poems, imitating the pastoral poetry of Theocritus the Syracusan <3rd cent. B.C.) Like all the great works of Vergil, these are written in hexameters, and it was the smoothness of the versification and the novelty of the subject which gained them their popularity. Vergil loved the country, and Maecenas made use of his taste to persuade him to write a long didactic poem on Agriculture——the Georyics—which describes in four books the management of crops, of trees and vines, of cattle and hores and of bees.
